f82"></a>2. Existing Solutions and Their Drawbacks</p><p>On 7 June 1742, in=
 a letter, the Russian mathematician Christian Goldbach was the first to st=
ate his conjecture to Leonhard Euler <a href=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journ=
al/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref3">[</a><a target=3D"_self" id=3D"r=
eturn2" href=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=3D13=
6153#ref3" class=3D"content_c3">3</a>]. On 30 June 1742, in a reply, Euler =
proposed the following conjecture =E2=80=9CEvery positive even integer can =
be written as the sum of two primes.=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CEvery integer gr=
eater than two can be written as the sum of three primes.=E2=80=9D <a href=
=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref4">[=
</a><a target=3D"_self" id=3D"return3" href=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journa=
l/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref4" class=3D"content_c4">4</a>]. At t=
hat time, 1 was considered to be a prime number. </p><p>Finally, Goldbach r=
emarked on his conjecture as below: =E2=80=9CEvery even integer greater tha=
n two can be written as the sum of two primes.=E2=80=9D Now, Goldbach=E2=80=
=99s conjecture has been split into two halves: </p><p>1) The Weak Goldbach=
 Conjecture asserts that all odd numbers greater than 7 are the sum of thre=
e odd primes. </p><p>2) The Strong Goldbach Conjecture asserts that every e=
ven integer greater than two can be written as the sum of two primes. </p><=
p>Until the 19th century, by the analytic number theory, people created a b=
reakthrough path in studying the Strong Goldbach Conjecture. Brun, in 1919 =
devised his new method using the =E2=80=9Csieve of Eratosthenes=E2=80=9D as=
 an asymptotic formula for the number of representations of <i>n</i> as the=
 sum of two numbers, neither divisible by any fixed number of primes <a hre=
f=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref5">=
[</a><a target=3D"_self" id=3D"return4" href=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journ=
al/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref5" class=3D"content_c5">5</a>]. Aft=
er that, many mathematicians improved Brun=E2=80=99s idea published. Follow=
ing, Chinese mathematician Jingrun Chen proved that every sufficiently larg=
e even integer is a sum of a prime and a product of at most 2 primes <a hre=
f=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref6">=
[</a><a target=3D"_self" id=3D"return5" href=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journ=
al/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref6" class=3D"content_c6">6</a>]. Thi=
s result shall be the best improvement now. However, people understand that=
 the sieve method is impossible to solve the Strong Goldbach Conjecture by =
some modifications of the current strategies. Hence, many people thought th=
at another new path should be found out to solve the Strong Goldbach Conjec=
ture problem. The Weak Goldbach Conjecture appeared to have been proved in =
2013 <a href=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=3D13=
6153#ref7">[</a><a target=3D"_self" id=3D"return6" href=3D"https://www.scir=
p.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref7" class=3D"content_c7">=
7</a>] <a href=3D"https://www.scirp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=3D=
136153#ref8">[</a><a target=3D"_self" id=3D"return7" href=3D"https://www.sc=
irp.org/journal/paperinformation?paperid=3D136153#ref8" class=3D"content_c8=
">8</a>], but the strong Goldbach Conjecture remains unproven. </p><p>Haral=
d Helfgott published a proof of Goldbach=E2=80=99s weak conjecture in 2013,=
 but it has not been published formally. </p><p>The present research mainly=
 uses the analytic number theory on the distribution of prime numbers. For =
any searching of the Strong Goldbach Conjecture, the probability of a Goldb=
ach partition inside among two closed intervals <span class=3D"MathJax_Prev=
